{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628651"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:59:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:59:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17231"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17231","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17231"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9921"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77598"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9921"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17231"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63111"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7615"},{"type":"tags","id":"10750"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23263"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23265"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77598"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENon-coding RNAs are important regulators of gene expression that do not produce proteins. These molecules are transcribed from DNA but never translated into protein products. MicroRNAs are a major class of small non-coding RNAs found in most eukaryotic cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism by which microRNAs regulate gene expression?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mediates messenger RNA splicing reactions","Enhances messenger RNA structural stability","Blocks messenger RNA translation via binding","Facilitates ribosomal RNA processing","Reorganises chromatin architecture"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks messenger RNA translation via binding\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of microRNA function. These molecules typically target specific sequences in the 3\u0027 untranslated region of messenger RNAs and either block protein synthesis or promote transcript degradation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMediates messenger RNA splicing reactions\u003C/strong\u003E - This is performed by spliceosomes, not microRNAs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhances messenger RNA structural stability\u003C/strong\u003E - MicroRNAs typically promote degradation rather than stabilisation of transcripts\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitates ribosomal RNA processing\u003C/strong\u003E - MicroRNAs are not involved in ribosomal RNA production\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReorganises chromatin architecture\u003C/strong\u003E - MicroRNAs act post-transcriptionally on messenger RNA, not on chromatin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMicroRNAs are part of a larger family of non-coding RNAs that includes long non-coding RNAs, small interfering RNAs, and other regulatory RNA species. Each class has distinct mechanisms for controlling gene expression.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["MicroRNAs are small non-coding RNAs that regulate gene expression by binding to complementary sequences in messenger RNA.","MicroRNAs primarily function to repress gene expression through translational inhibition or transcript degradation.","Non-coding RNAs are functional RNA molecules that do not encode proteins but play crucial regulatory roles in cells."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","O\u0027Brien J, Hayder H, Zayed Y, Peng C. Overview of MicroRNA Biogenesis, Mechanisms of Actions, and Circulation. Front Endocrinol (Lausanne). 2018 Aug 3;9:402. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6085463/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63111"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17231"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63111"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T20:12:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T20:13:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9921"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77598"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id"